1 2. Locating, relocating, establishing, or laying out the alignment
2 or elevation of any of the fixed works embraced within the
3 practice of professional engineering;
4 3. Making any survey for the subdivision of any tract of land,
5 including the topography, alignment and grades of streets and
6 incidental drainage within the subdivision, and the preparation
7 and perpetuation of maps, record plats, field note records, and
8 property descriptions that represent these surveys;
9 4. Determining, by the use of the principles of land surveying, the
10 position for any survey monument or reference point, or
11 setting, resetting, or replacing any survey monument or
12 reference point;
13 5. Determining the configuration or contour of the earth's surface
14 or the position of fixed objects on the earth's surface by
15 measuring lines and angles and applying the principles of
16 mathematics or photogrammetry;
17 6. Providing geodetic surveying which includes surveying for
18 determination of the size and shape of the earth both
19 horizontally and vertically and the precise positioning of points
20 on the earth utilizing angular and linear measurements through
21 spatially oriented spherical geometry; and
22 7. Creating, preparing, or modifying electronic or computerized
23 data, including land information systems and geographic
24 information systems relative to the performance of the practice
25 of land surveying.activities in sub-sub-subdivisions 1. through
26 6. of this sub-subdivision.
27 …."
28 SECTION 2.(b) G.S. 89C-13, as reenacted by Section 1(b) of this act, reads as
29 rewritten:
30 "§ 89C-13. General requirements for licensure.
31 (a) Engineer Intern. – To be certified as an engineer intern, an applicant shall (i) pass the
32 fundamentals of engineering examination and make application to the Board, (ii) be of good
33 character and reputation, (iii) submit three character references to the Board, one of whom is a
34 professional engineer, (iv) comply with the requirements of this Chapter, and (v) (iv) meet one
35 of the following requirements:
36 (1) Education. – Be a graduate of an EAC/ABET accredited engineering
37 curriculum or of a related science curriculum which has been approved by the
38 Board as being of satisfactory standing.
39 (2) Education and experience. – Be a graduate of an engineering curriculum or
40 related science curriculum of four years or more, other than curriculums
41 approved by the Board as being of satisfactory standing in subdivision (1) of
42 this subsection, and possess engineering experience satisfactory to the Board
43 with a specific record of four or more years of progressive experience on
44 engineering projects of a grade and character satisfactory to the Board.
45 …
46 (b) Land Surveyor Applicant. – The evaluation of a land surveyor applicant's
47 qualifications shall involve a consideration of the applicant's education, technical, and land
48 surveying experience, exhibits of land surveying projects with which the applicant has been
49 associated, and recommendations by references. The land surveyor applicant's qualifications may
50 be reviewed at an interview if the Board determines it necessary. Educational credit for institute
51 courses, correspondence courses, or other courses shall be determined by the Board.
